# Writing Style

Use formal academic language with high technical precision.

## Punctuation
- Never use emdashes. Use commas, semicolons, colons, or separate sentences instead.
- Use en-dashes only for numeric ranges (e.g., "pages 12--15").
- Prefer periods over semicolons when the clauses are not tightly coupled.

## AI Tropes to Avoid
Never use these words or phrases. They are tells of AI-generated text:
- "delve", "dive into", "deep dive"
- "landscape" (when not literal geography)
- "leverage" (use "use" or "employ")
- "utilize" (use "use" or "employ")
- "it's important to note", "it's worth noting", "notably"
- "in today's [anything]", "in the rapidly evolving"
- "game-changer", "paradigm shift", "cutting-edge", "groundbreaking"
- "seamless", "robust" (without quantification), "streamline"
- "foster", "bolster", "underpin", "spearhead"
- "a]comprehensive guide", "the ultimate guide"
- "in conclusion", "to summarize" (just state the conclusion)
- "Let's [verb]" in formal writing
- Starting paragraphs with "So," or "Now,"
- "This is because" at the start of a sentence (restructure to lead with the cause)

## Tone
- Complex, multi-clause sentences that build sophisticated arguments
- Lead with problem statements before presenting solutions
- Passive voice strategically for objectivity; active for clarity
- Acknowledge limitations before proposing alternatives

## Structure
- Define acronyms on first use: "engineered nanomaterials (ENMs)"
- Include quantitative details when discussing results
- Reference methodologies explicitly
- Use field-specific terminology without over-explaining

## Argumentation
- Build critiques constructively: acknowledge strengths before identifying limitations
- Distinguish between descriptive and predictive capabilities
- Frame problems in terms of analytical feasibility and practical constraints

## Vocabulary Preferences
- "comprise" over "make up"; "employ" over "use" (for methods)
- "constrained to" rather than "limited to"; "elucidate" for revealing understanding
- "feasible" for practical possibility; "mechanistic understanding" for causal relationships

## Diagrams
- Always use Mermaid flow diagrams when sketching out flow diagrams
